segments.text: Where did that recipe come from?
When did it originate?
And how many of those rolls were made a week or a day?
Well, I'd like to take credit for that, but I can't.
That roll was being produced when I came here.
And it's a fully approved roll, as you know.
It won't keep very well due to that because it's a fluffy, soft roll.
But that was used only at the Memorial Student Center.
We used a little different role for the remainder of the campus.
But that's a famous role even today.
So it started with the MSC, maybe?
Perhaps it did.
I do not know.
I wish I'd asked at the time who originated that role, and someday I may find out.
If I do, I'll come back and tell you.
When my wife and I moved to El Paso, somebody gave us a recipe.
Well, I sent you a recipe, but it seems like it's difficult to duplicate.
It was.
In another area for some reason.
It's like trying to eat lobster here or pinto beans in Maine.
They just aren't the same.
That's right.
What were other favorite dishes or
specialties down through the years?
Well, one of the main ones that I recall was the Aggie fritter.
And the Aggie fritter was nothing more.
It was served often at breakfast and was a favorite item.
It was two pieces of bread that was stuck together with apricot jam
and refrigerated overnight.
This toast then, these two slices of bread were cut diagonally, dipped in a batter similar to a hot cake batter, deep fat fried, and then sprinkled with sugar as they came out of the hot fat.
That was one of the most popular items.
I gave that to Luby's once when I started their breakfast.
And it was so popular here, this manager said, well, I wish the managers didn't want to call it Aggie Roll in the other parts of the country.
I told them to use it.
They had to call it that because that's what it is.
So that was about the old items.
Some of the strange items and unusual things we had here because A&M had been here so long.
and had purchased so much compared to other universities.
One of the items you'd run into some strange thing.
I noticed the item on our bid list, it said A&M Hounds, A&M Hounds.
An A&M Hound is not ham at all.
An A&M Hound was a baby beef leg set with a leg in the round.
And that became known as an A&M ham set.
So those are just some of the things that... Who were...
Describe for me the purchasing process, the procurement process for all of the food service supplies.
Well, we had competitive bids when I came in.
But that had been one of my specialties in the military, so we expanded that some and began to develop some specifications we didn't have.
And we began to buy as much as we could store with intensive competitive bidding.
And we would do this in the production seasons, packing seasons, as much as we could.
And then if we heard of distressed merchandise, that is overproduction of ketchup or peaches or whatever it was, we would take more bids.
And each year, one of the things we started was to get samples in from all these companies that bid.
We'd have a counter maybe 100 feet long or more of different foods.
And we'd start comparing, and we would weigh every item
that we were going to purchase that was weighable to determine the lowest cost per ounce of the product inside without juice or additives or anything.
And so we were very successful in getting some very inexpensive items.
I had one occasion to compare that with one of the main chain cafeteria operators who believed he could buy off from as he needed as cheap as we could.
So we compared figures one day, and we were paying about an average of 30% less than he was.
He said, I give up.
And he was a very wealthy, successful operator.
And then that's one of the reasons we built.
One of the last things that I had anything to do with was our food service commissary on the west side of campus.
And the nearest we could figure, the first year we
We built that because we had supplies scattered all over campus.
We estimated that we saved approximately one half million dollars that year.
Now you stored in it canned and frozen?
Canned and frozen, yes.
A year's supply of cans primarily and of course the frozen would vary anywhere from 30, 60 to 90 days.
because we've tried to get as large of lots as we could.
And it has been successful to the best of my knowledge and belief.
I was there about two or three years before I retired.
Did you ever buy bulk, dry vegetables, beans, corn, anything like that?
Not, not, not, not, we bought dry ones.
Yes, we bought like, you know, pintos and black-eyed peas.
Yes, we'd do that stuff.
One time I happened to be walking through and there was a little bit of bidding.
and I think it was bacon, and I think they were tenths of cents, 21 point something something cents per pound.
It's fractions of a hundredth of a cent.
Is that right?
Yeah.
Is that right?
Yeah.
Can you give me, give us some examples of the quantity per year you might have bought of anything?
Well, we'd buy 40 to 60,000 pounds of canned corn.
Per year?
Per year.
40 to 60,000 pounds of green beans.
Nearly everything was based on a body.
And we, as I recall, we were using about a carload lot, which is up to 60,000 pounds of many of our basic items.
And sometimes it would be a carload, but we would vary the amount of the car that would come in.
Because that saved, obviously, money on packing and shipping and such.
That was one of the things that we took advantage of in the carload lots.
And those materials would arrive by railroad or by truck?
When I speak of carloads, I'm talking of rail.
And we had a lot of rail shipments, more than I think they have now.
But then later on, it began to develop a lot of wood come by truck.
Sometimes it's in a couple of trucks.
Sometimes it'd be a truckload.
Normally, we could buy for less money with the rail car.
But that changes a little over periods of time.
Where else in this part of the country was there another operation of this magnitude other than in the military?
Well, Texas Tech had a similar operation.
Not as big.
We were...
about, we were one of the largest in America for institutional feet in one location.
Texas Tech was big.
The next one of any size would have been Michigan State, Ohio State, University of Illinois.
But beyond that, they were small by comparison.
So we couldn't
We couldn't work much with them, with others, except for those, to compare notes of things we did.
And we did that as much as possible.
We had an organization, which was National Association of College and University Food Services.
And I told some of them one day, I said, we have to stay close together because our food, us food service people are always on the bottom of the totem pole.
To which they agreed.
Now, and so food service here was entirely self-supporting.
Entirely.
And that not only meant daily operations, but
additions, renovations, improvements, and so forth.
Yes, that's right.
Take me through, in the nine-month term school year, take me through a typical week of your schedule.
Well, it's almost a blur because one of the jokes I used to, an ironical joke I guess you'd call it,
I had a heart attack on one occasion, I'd been working about 16 hours a day, and Dr. O.C.
Cooper says, you've got to take a half a day off.
So I told everybody, which is true really, I cut it from 16 to 12 to 13, because I could never feel that I accomplished a job on the list.
Now maybe if I'd been more intelligent I could have, but I couldn't.
We'd start out early in the morning.
I'd get up early in the morning, every morning.
I got up early in the morning.
If we were building something, like a renovation or a new building, I might wake up at 3 o'clock.
If I did, I'd get up and come to work.
But, ordinarily, I'd come in about 7 o'clock, sometimes 6.30, and try to visit
two or three places because my routine was to try to visit every place at least once a day.
And sometimes you can't do that, but this was the schedule anyway.
And there's always a bunch of paperwork for something when you have, as you know, a big number of employees.
So you get into that a little bit, and once you get a little bit drowsy or tired of that,
Then you've got to go out and see who's missing where.

And not because you have to do it personally, because it's good to, by that time the managers would be in gear, and I would simply want to ask them how they were doing, and how things were coming along, and if I could be of any help to them.
Then we'd come along for lunchtime, and I'd want to see some of the guests at different places.
If it was students, or if it was people, I'd want to circulate among them and see if everything was all right.
And then in the afternoon, we'd get back to the paperwork again.
And there's always plenty of paperwork.
And sometimes there'd be a question.
Not very often they'd come in from Howard or Mr. Cherry.
But that wasn't any problem, really, because they were trying to support.
They were not trying to interfere with anything.
And then by the time the evening meal came along, it was time to take another look at your customers and the menu, to check the menus.
We did this each time to see if the menu that we prescribed ahead of time was being followed.
And if so, what quality was.
So I tasted a lot of items that, you know, that really got to be a chore because you'd taste items so much you'd interfere with your meal.
I've tasted enough items so that some days I wouldn't eat at all or eat on the run and never sat down to eat a meal.
Just keep tasting maybe something that went wrong.

Then in the evening, if we had a banquet, particularly, or a formal affair, and we had these, really, in Sebiza and in Duncan and in the Memorial Student Center, I would want to see what was happening, even though we had competent managers, just to be there, because I found it was very important
just to be available so that questions came up, they could get an answer immediately.
I didn't have to wait and wonder where I was.
If anybody was unhappy about anything, that is a customer, I could say, well, I was there.
And I didn't know it, or I did know it, and I did this and so.
So that's the reason the hours were quite long.
So you'd get here
By 7.
About 7 o'clock.
And you'd leave?
Anywhere from, really anywhere from 7 to 10 or 10 o'clock.
All right, let's make it then a football Saturday.
What was Saturday like?
That was a long, that was extra long because I used to tell people anytime we had a football game,
A big day before, everybody was woozy the next day, which was pretty well true because everybody did everything they could possibly do to be sure it was done right.
And you'd have to shift people and equipment.
We would have a meeting each Friday.
I started a meeting each of our managers each Friday so that if we had a banquet one place, we'd have to shift equipment over to another and shift personnel as well.
And we had to do this methodically and pretty accurately in order to survive.
And I'm sure they're doing that today.
What were the most popular dishes, be they desserts or main courses or what, that you recall?
We mentioned the rolls, but... Well, the rolls are good.
Always a steak was popular.
We started out, when I came here, serving a 12-ounce steak, and at 14, that would be ridiculous now, down to 6 and 8 ounces.
But the steak was always very popular.
Lobster Troubadour, very popular.
Lobster Newberg.
And the shrimp fries we had were real popular items, whereas the
pluck them off like peanuts, the big, big shrimp.
And Mr. Howard liked those particularly well.
And of course the big rounds of roast beef were always a popular item.
Now they're more popular then than they are now because people eat lighter today.
And then we had a lot of desserts that were more popular.
Things like certainly the chocolate pies and pecan pies and
the coconuts that people liked the recipes a little better, and they were quite popular as well.
And then we had, I remember, always for the football games for a long period there, we would serve and call it Aggie cake, which is a maroon colored red velvet cake.
And we'd have that lined up with the white icing on it.
That'd always been popular because
People bought it because it was maroon.
Maroon and white.
Did President and Mrs. Rutter have any favorites, particularly?
Well, President Rutter's favorite was just food.
He liked all food.
I recall one occasion when I'd serve teriyaki.
I brought this recipe from the east.
He thought that was great, and we were having it.
President's Buffet, and he was sitting in the back, and I think that day he was eating with Governor Smith or somebody.
But he got up from his table, and I was at one end of the room, and he was the other, and he said, Hey, Dollar, what is this?
I hollered back and told him.
Were there any that either of the rudders didn't like?
that you knew to leave them?
No, not really.
No, they had no hang-ups.
They seemed to be prone to roast beef a lot.
Ms. Runner liked to always have that on hand.
But they were really easy to, very particular, but still easy to satisfy.
All right, let's go then to the Williams.
Did they have any special enjoyments?
Well, yes, they...
They were a little more particular and wanted certain things and didn't go for the heavy food as much.
And of course then the Vandiver's were not too much on the heavy food.
Then Dr. Miller, when Dr. Miller was here, he was back to the type of President Rudder.
He liked to eat and eat well and have it in the old fashioned, old fashioned manner.
So of course we tried to please everybody.
All right, now this next question has pluses and minuses.
Sure.
You must remember some notable successes, and there must have been at least one or two incidents when something didn't work out the way you'd planned it.
Yeah, well, I think the most embarrassing thing that ever happened to me, fortunately there wasn't a lot of them.
I always envisioned the fact that if we forgot a banquet scheduled or something.
We never did.
But that always was a harassment in the back of my mind.
But on one occasion, we had the knife and fork club up there.
And the chicken cordon bleu had just come out, so they decided that was the menu.
And so we said, okay.
And it had always been turned out, and it always turned out very pretty, and we knew just how to do it.
We had a chef had been doing it for years.
Lo and behold, that product,
looked well on the plate, but it wasn't cooked.
That was the most embarrassing thing that ever happened to me.
So this was raw chicken?
Well, it was partially raw at any rate.
But, you know, none of it did not seem to bother any of them very much.
But the irony, the peculiar part about this is
It seemed like always the things I thought were going to give me the most trouble didn't.
It was always the unexpected that gave me the great problems.
Of course, I guess that's true everywhere, but it had never been true on the other jobs I'd had as much as this one.
Among the groups, what's about some of the largest meals that you remember having to prepare for?
Oh, I believe maybe 1,500 at a time, which is not too many.
That would have been in Duncan?
In Duncan, and sometimes in Sabeza we'd have that many.

uh as a but not seated at one one time now actually sabiza will seat where would it then uh maximum seating 4200 whole target that seated doesn't really uh that's a wall-to-wall family style and duncan would seat 3 800. he fed that many during the second world war when the navy and marines were here training
I talked to him once.
I used to have him out as often as I could before he passed away.
Let's go back and capture him.
Describe him physically and his manner and style of leadership.
Well, he was tall, very well-dressed, well-mannered individual, well-educated man.
And he was fairly formal in his conduct.

with everybody and and really easy to interpret misinterpret because he was had a little bit of a harsh side but he had really a heart of gold he's one of those people that wanted things exactly right but he would anybody's trying he would support them to the last but if unless it was it unless they were violating his opinion and that would infuriate him greatly
And there's some instances that some of his other people related to him, and I could see that as we went along.
But if he thought he could do something for you, he would do that.
But he gave very clear instructions, and he did not give real close supervision.
As a matter of fact, he had the reputation of getting bored with the job after he'd been around too long for a while.
But he knew...
How to operate.

As you may know, he was hired out of here by White's Cafeterias at a then tremendous salary, $25,000 a year, which is about the same as the governor of the state made, and higher than anybody else made anywhere.
So we were just amazed at his reputation.
He had a tremendous reputation.
Now, he was here about how long?
I don't know how many years he was here.
He came from New Orleans, I believe.
I was going to say you and he and Bernard Sabisa together.
For a long time.
Bernard Sabisa was a good director 50 years.
I was going to say the three of you, about three-fourths, two-thirds, three-fourths of the existence.
Of the whole time.
Because Mr. Holtard was here 15 years or something?
I think so, but I'm not too certain about that.

uh i was a seventh director by the way we had general b he was the first then sabiza then mr duncan and mr hotard and then frank nuget i believe and then me who'd i leave out of there somebody i think at least there's someone we had to i'll redo that b sabiza duncan hotard penniston penniston and news news jay penniston was hotard brother-in-law
Oh, I didn't know.
He had run the meat market.
Okay.
We had a central butcher shop, by the way.
You mentioned we didn't cook it there.
By the way, what they do now, and before I left here, we started cooking a lot centrally, the meat roast and the hamburgers.
As a matter of fact, we have a great ground meat operation there.
We use chucks primarily.
I think they still do.
And, uh, under real sanitary conditions.
And it's packaged and been sent out to the, uh, dormitory, uh, to the mess hall.
During your, your days, did we ever have any breakdown of quality control and people get sick?
And did we ever have an outbreak of anything?
We didn't have any big outbreaks, but we, we had a, we had a few where, where, uh,
But nothing was ever identified as having caused it.
And what I did, when we suspected something, I'd get the food sanitarium here on campus to look at it and arrange for any tests that needed to be done.
So we precluded most of that.
Actually, there's seldom really any chance for that if your sanitation is good enough.
Now, I know there's always a chance for anything, but we were very blessed to not have any serious things developed.
Let's make believe there's going to be a big dinner on Saturday.
The president's going to host it.
We've got a number of dignitaries coming.
who would select the menu and how far in advance would you need to start planning it?
Well, of course, we would coordinate with the, or vice versa, with the president's secretary or assistant to work out the basic menu.
If it's a buffet, we had free reign.
But if it's a seated affair, it would be different.
So that would usually happen and should happen maybe a week or two in advance, just traditionally.
Not necessarily so.
We could do that within 48 hours easy enough.
But was it routine only a week in advance for you and your staff to sit down?
About that.
That was sort of routine, not essential.
But we would have an idea about the number, and we would keep talking almost daily with whoever we worked with in the president's office.
about the numbers or any peculiarities or menu preferences such as could they eat meats or did they want fish instead of steak or vegetables instead of regular meal.
And so if you worked closely enough and worked on it enough,

things always went well but it was always a matter of intense effort and I we always did that to my knowledge to try to get them right now and that doesn't mean they were all they weren't perfect but they were they were acceptable you might say all right so you would with uh when NELDA
Rowell, now Nelda Green, was the secretary.
You would work primarily with her?
Normally with Ed Cooper.
With Ed Cooper, okay.
All right, now let's make believe that you have some new idea, some new dish that has never been tried before.
were the presidents susceptible to those, to trying them?
Well, I wouldn't want to do that on a big affair.
Oh, okay.
I wouldn't mind serving him personally.
Oh, okay.
On one occasion, I came up with a concoction for the Board of Regents a few years ago over here, and I called it Egg's Regency.
It was an egg, nothing more than one had been...
scrambled and shaped with a sauce of breakfast on them.
So Mr. Weizenbaker came in and who was a difficult with some people, but Mr. Burkhardt said, how would you like to try our egg Regency?
He said, oh yeah, I'll try that.
But he said, leave that old sauce off.
Well, that was the whole thing.
As the board members would come in that morning,
Mr. Burkhart kept laughing about it.
Mr. Burkhart would say, don't treat that egg green, see.
But, you see, most of the people, as you know, you've been at that level.
When you reach that level, it's just like the generals in the Army.
The easiest people to talk with and to get along with, as long as you're trying, are the people on top.
Mm-hmm.
And, of course, if you do something to negligence, that's a different story.
But that's the thing that always bothered me, that we would foul up.
And I guess that's maybe the reason the Lord blessed me when I didn't.
All right.
Let's go back now to you reported Howard Vestal.
and Mr. Cherry, give me an example of Mr. Cherry's decision-making style, some important decision that he made that affected you and food service.
Well, there were a lot of them.
I made notes on everything but that.
But he would make the decisions, I'd say almost the final decision, except Mr. and Mr.
Rudder, if it was big enough, would get in on it.
on anything we were to build, for example.

If we had a new building of some type, that would be of concern to him in the sense that he wouldn't know why we were doing it and where we were going to put it and what it would cost and if we had the money and that sort of thing.
And if it sounded good to him,
He's like Howard Bestel said once, and I'll interrupt this to say this.
He said, let's don't take Mr. Cherry, the small problems, let's take him the big ones.
Because he had a method of handling the biggest problems, the easiest of any man I have ever seen.
I have never seen a man that was as calm and deliberate
and seems to be as active as he was on nearly everything.
